'''''Torpedo Fire''''' is a turn-based submarine warfare game written by John Lyon for the [[Apple II]] and published by [[Strategic Simulations]] in 1981.<ref name=giantlist/>

==Gameplay==
''Torpedo Fire'' is a game in which a submarine attack against a convoy is simulated.<ref name="SG"/> It is designed for two players, each turn covering 60 seconds of simulation time.<ref name=proctor/>

==Reception==
Forrest Johnson reviewed ''Torpedo Fire'' in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' No. 41.<ref name="SG">{{cite journal|last=Johnson |first=Forrest |date=July 1981 |title=Capsule Reviews|journal=[[The Space Gamer]]|publisher=[[Steve Jackson Games]]|issue=41|pages=36}}</ref> Johnson commented that "I cannot help but feel that Strategic Simulations has taken a wrong turn somewhere. I hope they find their way again soon."<ref name="SG"/> In ''Video Games'', Rich Sutton said playability concerns meant that he "only recommended [''Torpedo Fire''] for the advanced player who desires the most accurate simulation on the market".<ref name=videogames>{{cite journal | author=Sutton, Rich | title=War Games: A Battle Plan for Attacking Video Simulations | volume=2 | number=1 | date=October 1993 | journal=Video Games | pages=40, 41, 44–48 }}</ref>

Bob Proctor, in a detailed analysis for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', concluded "Although extremely well conceived, the concepts could have been better implemented. "<ref name=proctor/>

